1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,288
you'd develop a $600 million business in producing greenhouses, and perhaps a $250 million industry supplying plants and seeds.

2
00:00:10,879 --> 00:00:17,970
The only difficulty with this exercise is that the group, ten minutes before completely cold about greenhouses,

3
00:00:18,159 --> 00:00:22,528
now is so enthusiastic they don't want to move on to the next subject.

4
00:00:23,440 --> 00:00:28,769
Use the dig into a deeper technique to develop enthusiasm toward other people.

5
00:00:29,200 --> 00:00:33,570
Find out all you can about another person, what he does, his family,

6
00:00:33,600 --> 00:00:41,249
his background, his ideas and ambitions, and you'll find your interest in and enthusiasm about him mounting.

7
00:00:41,600 --> 00:00:45,249
Keep digging and you're certain to find some common interests.

8
00:00:45,279 --> 00:00:49,570
Keep digging and you'll eventually discover a fascinating person.

9
00:00:50,639 --> 00:00:57,009
The dig-into-it-deeper technique works also in developing enthusiasm toward new places.

10
00:00:57,519 --> 00:01:03,889
Several years ago, some young friends of mine decided to move from Detroit to a small town in mid-Florida.

11
00:01:03,919 --> 00:01:10,210
They sold their home, closed out their business connections, said goodbye to their friends, and were gone.

12
00:01:11,039 --> 00:01:13,889
Six weeks later they were back in Detroit.

13
00:01:14,080 --> 00:01:16,450
The reason had nothing to do with employment.

14
00:01:16,560 --> 00:01:21,330
Rather, as they put it, we just couldn't stand living in a small town.

15
00:01:21,440 --> 00:01:24,129
Besides, all our friends are in Detroit.

16
00:01:24,159 --> 00:01:25,970
We just had to come back.

17
00:01:26,720 --> 00:01:33,810
In later conversations with these people, I learned the real reason why they didn't like the small Florida city.

18
00:01:33,919 --> 00:01:38,929
During their short stay there, they had taken only a surface view of the community,

19
00:01:39,039 --> 00:01:42,528
its history, its plans for the future, its people.

20
00:01:42,799 --> 00:01:47,730
They moved their bodies to Florida, but left their minds in Detroit.

21
00:01:48,879 --> 00:01:58,289
I've talked with dozens of executives, engineers, and salesmen who have developed career trouble because their companies want to move them to another location,

22
00:01:58,320 --> 00:01:59,810
but they don't want to go.

23
00:02:00,320 --> 00:02:05,249
I just can't see moving to Chicago, or San Francisco, or Atlanta,

24
00:02:05,249 --> 00:02:09,970
or New York, or Miami, is a remark spoken many times a day.

25
00:02:10,799 --> 00:02:14,528
There's one way to build enthusiasm toward a new location.

26
00:02:14,720 --> 00:02:17,810
Simply resolve to dig into the new community.

27
00:02:18,080 --> 00:02:19,649
Learn all you can about it.

28
00:02:19,759 --> 00:02:21,090
Mix with the people.

29
00:02:21,360 --> 00:02:26,289
Make yourself feel and think like a community citizen from the very first day.

30
00:02:26,480 --> 00:02:30,610
Do this, and you'll be enthusiastic about your new environment.

31
00:02:31,519 --> 00:02:35,730
Today, millions of Americans invest in corporate securities.

32
00:02:35,919 --> 00:02:40,370
But there are many millions more who have no interest at all in the stock market.

33
00:02:40,720 --> 00:02:46,690
That's because they are people who have not familiarized themselves with what the securities market is,

34
00:02:46,879 --> 00:02:51,090
how it operates, the day-to-day romance of American business.

35
00:02:51,919 --> 00:02:57,810
To get enthusiasm about anything—people, places, things—dig into it deeper.

36
00:02:58,240 --> 00:03:01,889
Dig into it deeper, and you'll develop enthusiasm.

